          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">German far right sues</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>Summary: The far-right AfD party has filed a lawsuit against its intelligence agency over an ‚Äúextremist‚Äù label. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The Alternative for Germany (AfD) party <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-may-25-spotlight-h2-3-is-suing" target="_blank">is suing</a> Germany's domestic intelligence agency (BfV). The agency labeled the party a "right-wing extremist" group, which could lead to more surveillance and political isolation, affecting the party's image before the upcoming elections. The agency's report classified the party as a racist and anti-Muslim organisation.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The move means the ruling coalition could limit or halt public funding for the AfD. The opposition party questioned the intelligence agencies' power to label political groups. While German lawmakers want to ban the AfD, the constitution court guidelines say a party must exhibit a "combative and aggressive" nature to implement a ban, which the party has stayed clear of.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Meanwhile, Germany‚Äôs center-left party (SPD) has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-may-25-spotlight-h2-4-confirmed-its-ministers" target="_blank">confirmed its ministers</a> for the coalition government led by Chancellor-designate Friedrich Merz. Some of the key appointments are:</p>
          <ul style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5; padding-left:20px;">
          <li>Lars Klingbeil as FM and Vice Chancellor</li>
          <li>Boris Pistorius, who keeps the Defense Ministry</li>
          <li>B√§rbel Bas leading Labor and Social Affairs</li>
          <li>Stefanie Hubig as Justice Minister</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          This lineup ensures regional representation, party unity, and policy continuity in the conservative-led government. Friedrich Merz, who was expected to be sworn in, lost the majority in the first round of voting to pick the chancellor.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
