        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
          Do movies have geopolitical implications?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/the-interview-movie-north-korea-geopolitical-controversy.png" alt="A scene from The Interview, a satirical film whose fictional plot about assassinating North Korea‚Äôs leader sparked real-world geopolitical tension" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>A scene from The Interview, a satirical film whose fictional plot about assassinating North Korea‚Äôs leader sparked real-world geopolitical tension. Credits: THE CANADIAN PRESS/Darryl Dyck</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
         Movies and geopolitics are closely linked. Movies can be a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-may-25-foundations-h1-12-soft-power" target="_blank">soft power</a> used by governments to promote certain narratives. Cinema often reflects and shapes how people view international events. Hollywood has long depicted the American military fighting against the Russian villain, which projects that Russians are evil-minded.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        These subtle hints acted as a political influence over time, especially towards the end of the Cold War in the 1980s. The Cold War led to spy thrillers and nuclear dramas. Meanwhile, China has built a growing industry of state-supported films to boost national pride and reinforce its political messages. Russia uses historical dramas and war films to foster patriotism and support its geopolitical views.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Conversely, real-world geopolitical changes affect film narratives. After 9/11, movies about terrorism, intelligence, and Middle Eastern conflicts rose. Themes such as cyberwarfare, climate change, and authoritarianism have started taking shape in movies recently.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Erich Schwartzel‚Äôs nonfiction book, <i>Red Carpet: Hollywood, China, and the Global Battle for Cultural Supremacy</i>, examines China‚Äôs <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-may-25-foundations-h1-13-rising-influence" target="_blank">rising influence</a> on Hollywood and the global film scene. US studios seek to tap into China's rich market, so they often adjust their content to prevent upsetting Beijing. Schwartzel called this ‚Äúanticipatory censorship.‚Äù The book shows how Chinese political goals subtly change global entertainment, affecting everything from casting to storylines.</p>
        </mj-text>
